    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A War Over Rent, on Two Coasts</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Thomas Connor letter scores Paul Krugman's proposal to solve housing problem in San Francisco by letting apartments go to the highest bidder (June 7 Op-Ed column)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Rent Affair'' (column, June 7): Paul Krugman's suggestion that the highest bidder should get each apartment, and that there should be no rent control, demonstrates exactly why we need it.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Rent Affair'' (column, June 7): Paul Krugman's suggestion that the highest bidder should get each apartment, and that there should be no rent control, demonstrates exactly why we need it.</p>
        <p>What does he think would happen to the elderly, the poor and anyone who isn't wealthy? I guess he feels we should disappear. But we vote,  and many politicians who are against rent control disappear.</p>
        <p>THOMAS CONNOR  New York, June 7, 2000</p>
      </block>
